@* THE SILENT DIVERGENCE decision 167 CLOSED, found by PROBING the eleven spec 3 non-goals ADR 0003
   declared closed (register defect A12).

   <CascadingValue IsFixed="true"> used to compile at exit 0 with NO diagnostic, emitting the exact
   bytes the same source without IsFixed emits -- the attribute erased, not implemented. Measured
   against Blazor on this very shape:

     BLAZOR   : {"initial":{"a":"1","b":"1"},"afterClick1":{"a":"1","b":"2"},"afterClick2":{"a":"1","b":"3"}}
     FILAMENT : {"initial":{"a":"1","b":"1"},"afterClick1":{"a":"2","b":"2"},"afterClick2":{"a":"3","b":"3"}}

   IsFixed IS NOT "read the value once". A fixed cascade registers no subscription, so #a -- whose own
   [Parameter] Tag never changes and which is therefore never re-parameterised -- never sees a new
   value. #b's Tag DOES change on every click, so Blazor re-parameterises it and re-supplies the
   supplier's LIVE value: it advances 1 -> 2 -> 3 UNDER A FIXED CASCADE.

   THE OBVIOUS FIX IS ALSO WRONG, AND THAT IS WHY THIS IS A REFUSAL. Folding the value once at mount
   (`const _casc0 = level.value;`) renders 1,1,1 for BOTH consumers: right for #a, wrong for #b. A
   cascade here is LEXICAL SCOPE inlined into one mount(), and there is no per-consumer render pass
   for "re-supplied on re-parameterisation" to attach to. Refused, located on the IsFixed value, with
   the remedy in the message.

   Supported/Gate/CascadeTwoConsumers.razor is THE SAME FILE WITHOUT IsFixed, and it compiles: this
   fixture refuses for IsFixed and for nothing else.

   VALID BLAZOR: dotnet build of this source in a real Blazor WebAssembly project succeeds. *@
<div id="wrap"><CascadingValue Value="@level" IsFixed="true"><GaugeA Tag="static" /><GaugeB Tag="@tick" /></CascadingValue><button id="inc" @onclick="Inc">inc</button></div>

@code {
    private int level = 1;
    private string tick = "t";
    void Inc() { level++; tick = tick + "!"; }
}
